Certainly! To extend your existing Godmode Agentic Orchestrator with:

Role-based API access control (e.g., user roles and permissions per API route and function),
Agent Functions for scraping your Notebook LM or any URL,
Ability to invoke these scrape agents securely with role enforcement,
here’s a detailed plan, design, and sample implementation.

1. API Roles and Permissions Model
You need:

A user / identity model with assigned roles (e.g., admin, scraper, viewer).
A centralized authorization middleware or function to check roles/permissions before executing sensitive endpoints or agent actions.
A flexible roles-to-function-permissions mapping to drive access control dynamically.
Enforcement at all entry points (e.g., REST API, agent execution).
Example roles and permission functions:

| Role | Permissions / Allowed Functions | |-----------|--------------------------------------------------| | admin | All permissions including panic reset, full logs | | scraper | Can execute scrape agents, can schedule scans | | viewer | Can only query scan results and logs |

2. Agent Functions to Scrape Notebook LM and URLs
You want agents, e.g.:

notebookScraperAgent - scrapes and processes your notebook LM content.
urlScraperAgent - scrapes arbitrary URLs following safe policies (e.g., domain whitelist).
These agent modules define:

run(action, userId, context) — performs scraping.
onFail — fallback logic.
3. Implementation Outline and Sample Code
Backend additions:
a) User & Role Model and Permission Check
Add (e.g., in auth/roles.ts):

// Simple in-memory user store (demo only)
const userStore = new Map<string, { roles: string[] }>([
  ['adminUser', { roles: ['admin'] }],
  ['scraperUser', { roles: ['scraper'] }],
  ['viewerUser', { roles: ['viewer'] }],
]);

// Permission matrix: role => allowed agent functions
const rolePermissions: Record<string, string[]> = {
  admin: ['*'], // all permissions
  scraper: ['notebookScraperAgent', 'urlScraperAgent', 'culturalScanAgent'],
  viewer: [],
};

export function getUserRoles(userId: string) {
  return userStore.get(userId)?.roles || [];
}

export function userHasPermission(userId: string, agentName: string): boolean {
  const roles = getUserRoles(userId);
  if (roles.includes('admin')) return true;
  return roles.some(role => {
    const perms = rolePermissions[role] || [];
    return perms.includes(agentName) || perms.includes('*');
  });
}
b) Integrate Authorization in safeExecuteAgent
Update safeExecuteAgent (in agents/execute.ts):

import { userHasPermission } from '../auth/roles';

export async function safeExecuteAgent(agent: Agent, action: string, userId: string, context?: any) {
  if (!userHasPermission(userId, agent.name)) {
    return { error: `User ${userId} lacks permission to execute ${agent.name}` };
  }
  // ... rest of your safeExecuteAgent code unchanged
}
c) Sample notebookScraperAgent
import axios from 'axios';
import { Agent } from './types';

export const notebookScraperAgent: Agent = {
  name: 'notebookScraperAgent',
  run: async (action, userId, context) => {
    // action could specify specific notebook page or data
    const pageUrl = context?.pageUrl || 'https://your.notebook.lm/page';
    // Simple GET request to fetch content
    const response = await axios.get(pageUrl);
    // Here parse/process content as needed for your LM
    return { status: 'success', dataLength: response.data.length, snippet: response.data.substring(0, 200) };
  },
  onFail: async (action, userId, err) => {
    return { status: 'fail', message: err.message };
  }
};
d) Sample urlScraperAgent
import axios from 'axios';

const allowedDomains = ['example.com', 'mytrustedsource.org', 'your.notebook.lm'];

export const urlScraperAgent: Agent = {
  name: 'urlScraperAgent',
  run: async (action, userId, context) => {
    const scrapeUrl = context?.url;
    if (!scrapeUrl) throw new Error('URL parameter missing.');
    const parsed = new URL(scrapeUrl);
    if (!allowedDomains.includes(parsed.hostname)) {
      throw new Error(`Domain ${parsed.hostname} not allowed.`);
    }
    const response = await axios.get(scrapeUrl);
    return { status: 'success', url: scrapeUrl, contentLength: response.data.length };
  },
  onFail: async (action, userId, err) => {
    return { status: 'fail', message: err.message };
  }
};
e) Register these agents in your agents registry:
import { notebookScraperAgent } from './notebookScraperAgent';
import { urlScraperAgent } from './urlScraperAgent';

export const agents: Record<string, Agent> = {
  echoAgent: { /* your echo agent */ },
  notebookScraperAgent,
  urlScraperAgent,
  // other agents...
};
4. Security Considerations
Rate-limit scraping actions.
Validate all inputs in context before making network calls.
Whitelist trusted domains.
Require valid JWT with roles in API calls.
Avoid scraping untrusted/unrestricted URLs.
5. Usage Example
User sends:

POST /execute
{
  "agentName": "notebookScraperAgent",
  "action": "fetchPage",
  "userId": "scraperUser",
